## Abstract

This document presents a research program that identifies deep structural connections between information geometry, algebraic topology, non-equilibrium thermodynamics, and computational complexity. The program proposes that diverse computational phenomena — from neural network training to constraint satisfaction to phase transitions in statistical mechanics — are governed by shared geometric and topological structures. We formalize this through a collection of interconnected patterns, each grounded in established mathematics, each making specific testable predictions, and each accompanied by a clear assessment of its current epistemic status. The program's unifying aspirations remain conjectural, but its individual predictions are concrete, falsifiable, and experimentally accessible. We present three complete experimental protocols designed to test the program's strongest claims.

