### Pattern 7: Spectral Universality Classes of Iterative Methods (🟢)

**Core claim:** The empirical spectral distribution (ESD) of the Jacobian of an iterative method determines its universality class, which in turn determines its convergence behavior.

**Formalization:**

For an iterative method with state update $\mathbf{x}^{(k+1)} = G(\mathbf{x}^{(k)})$, the Jacobian $J = DG$ at the fixed point determines the local dynamics. In high dimensions, the ESD of $J$ converges to one of several universal distributions:

| Universality Class | ESD Shape | Convergence Behavior | Example Methods |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Elliptic** | Ellipse in complex plane | Damped oscillations | Newton-type methods |
| **Circular** | Uniform on disk | Isotropic decay | SGD with isotropic noise |
| **Marchenko-Pastur** | Bounded support $[a,b]$ | Structured decay | Layer-wise methods |
| **Tracy-Widom edge** | Semi-circle with sharp edge | Critical slowing | Methods at stability boundary |

**Prediction:** The universality class of an iterative method can be determined from the ESD of its Jacobian, and transitions between classes correspond to qualitative changes in convergence behavior.

**Status:** Well-established in random matrix theory. The specific application to iterative methods and the prediction of class transitions are novel but grounded in rigorous mathematics.

