### Pattern 10: Algorithmic Thermodynamic Equivalence (🟡)

**Core claim:** For any function $f$, the time–energy product of any physically realizable computation satisfies:

$$W_{\text{diss}} \cdot T \geq c \cdot K(f)^2$$

where $K(f)$ is the Kolmogorov complexity of $f$ and $c$ is a universal constant.

**Formalization:**

Combining the thermodynamic bound $W_{\text{diss}} \geq k_B T \ln 2 \cdot K(f)$ (from Pattern 1) with the time bound $T \geq C \cdot K(f)$ (each step processes $O(1)$ bits of information), we obtain:

$$W_{\text{diss}} \cdot T \geq c \cdot K(f)^2$$

**Implication:** This defines a **time–energy–complexity triangle**: for any computation, the three quantities $W$, $T$, and $K(f)$ satisfy a hyperbolic relationship. Different implementations of the same function cluster on the same hyperbola.

**Status:** The individual bounds are established; their combination into a joint bound is new but follows directly. The main challenge is that the Kolmogorov complexity is uncomputable, so the bound is not directly testable. It serves as a theoretical limit rather than a practical tool.

