## 5. The Pluralistic Decision Framework

The framework does not claim universal applicability. Instead, it provides a decision tree for determining when geometric analysis is appropriate:

```
Given a computational problem f:
│
├─ Is f naturally embedded in a smooth manifold? (Type 1)
│   Examples: Neural network training, physical simulation, Bayesian inference
│   → Full geometric framework applies. Predictions are quantitative.
│
├─ Is f the limit of a family of discrete problems? (Type 2)
│   Examples: Large-width neural networks, thermodynamic limits, random matrix ensembles
│   → Framework applies with finite-size corrections of O(n^{-1/2}).
│
├─ Does f admit a natural polynomial encoding? (Type 3b)
│   Examples: SAT instances, polynomial optimization, algebraic systems
│   → Algebraic-geometric tools apply. Predictions are qualitative.
│
└─ Is f adversarially designed to lack structure? (Type 3a)
    Examples: Cryptographic hash functions, one-way functions by design
    → Framework is silent. Different tools are needed.
```

The boundary between these regimes is itself informative: it tells us when geometric thinking is productive and when combinatorial or probabilistic methods are more appropriate.

